-- Apex Advantage — DPE Question Bank Expansion, Batch 2 of ~4 (v11)
--
-- Continues the expansion started in supabase-portal-schema-v10.sql
-- (72 -> 122 questions). This batch covers Pilot Qualifications
-- (eligibility, +12), Airworthiness Requirements (+12), Performance
-- and Limitations (+12), and Cross-Country Flight Planning (+14) --
-- 50 questions, no new categories needed since all four already exist.
--
-- Running total after this batch: 172 of ~250.
-- Remaining for batch 3/4: privileges/"Regulations" (+22), the rest of
-- Airspace (+9), Weather (+7), Aircraft Systems (+13), and ADM (+30).
--
-- Every question was checked against the existing 72, the 50 from
-- v10, and the free "10 Questions DPEs Love to Ask" guide already
-- live in the portal for topical overlap. One draft question was
-- rewritten after it turned out to closely echo a specific example
-- (a 1,850 ft / 2,200 ft runway scenario) already used verbatim in
-- that free guide's own "Apex Challenge" questions.
--
-- Run this in the Supabase SQL editor, after supabase-portal-schema-v10.

insert into public.dpe_questions (id, category, question, model_answer, common_mistakes, dpe_evaluating, acs_reference, real_world_application, is_scenario, scenario_order, sort_order) values

  -- ═══════════════════ ELIGIBILITY / PILOT QUALIFICATIONS (+12) ═══════════════════
  ('elig-9', 'eligibility', 'You''re 16 years old and have completed all your training requirements early. Can you take your Private Pilot checkride today?', 'No — you must be at least 17 years old to be issued a Private Pilot Certificate, even if all training and experience requirements are otherwise complete. You could take the checkride once you turn 17, but the FAA requires the age minimum for certificate issuance, and in practice a DPE won''t conduct a practical test for an applicant who won''t yet meet eligibility at the time of the test.', 'Confusing "completed training" with "eligible for the certificate," since age is an independent, non-negotiable eligibility requirement separate from training completion.', 'Whether you know eligibility requirements are a checklist of independent conditions, not just proficiency.', 'Area of Operation I, Task A — Pilot Qualifications (Knowledge).', 'A DPE won''t conduct a checkride for an applicant who isn''t yet eligible for the certificate regardless of skill level — confirming eligibility before scheduling saves everyone wasted time and money.', true, null, 8),
  ('elig-10', 'eligibility', 'What is the difference between the aeronautical experience requirements for a Private Pilot Certificate obtained through a Part 61 provider versus a Part 141 approved school?', 'Part 61 requires a minimum of 40 hours total flight time, with specific dual and solo minimums such as 3 hours of cross-country and 3 hours of night training. Part 141 approved training programs can qualify a student with as few as 35 hours total time, since the FAA-approved structured curriculum is credited with more efficient training, though specific dual/solo splits still apply per the approved course.', 'Assuming the requirements are identical regardless of the training pathway, or not knowing which pathway you actually trained under.', 'Whether you know which specific requirements actually apply to you, not a generic answer for a different pathway.', 'Area of Operation I, Task A — Pilot Qualifications (Knowledge).', 'Applicants sometimes cite the wrong minimums for their own training pathway — knowing your own path''s actual requirement is what avoids an embarrassing correction on checkride day.', false, null, 9),
  ('elig-11', 'eligibility', 'Your logbook shows your most recent flight review was completed 25 months ago, and you haven''t flown since. Can you act as pilot in command today?', 'No — a flight review must be completed within the preceding 24 calendar months. At 25 months you''re outside that window and aren''t current to act as PIC until you complete a new flight review, or its equivalent, such as completing a checkride for an additional rating.', 'Confusing the 24-calendar-month flight review requirement with other currency requirements like the 90-day passenger-carrying currency, which is a separate, shorter-window requirement.', 'Whether you can correctly apply the specific calendar-month window without confusing it with other currency rules.', 'Area of Operation I, Task A — Pilot Qualifications (Knowledge and Risk Management).', 'Letting a flight review lapse is a common, easily avoidable way for an otherwise experienced pilot to become illegal to act as PIC.', true, null, 10),
  ('elig-12', 'eligibility', 'What is the difference between a certificate and a rating, and can you give an example of each?', 'A certificate establishes your basic pilot privileges and grade, such as Private Pilot or Commercial Pilot. A rating is an authorization added to a certificate for a specific category, class, or type of aircraft, or an additional privilege such as an instrument rating. You could hold a Private Pilot certificate with an airplane single-engine land rating and later add an instrument rating without changing your underlying certificate.', 'Using "certificate" and "rating" interchangeably, or describing a rating as if it were a separate, stand-alone certificate.', 'Whether you understand the structural relationship between certificates and ratings, since applicants often blur the two.', 'Area of Operation I, Task A — Pilot Qualifications (Knowledge).', 'Knowing this distinction matters when reading your own certificate and understanding exactly what privileges and limitations actually apply to you.', false, null, 11),
  ('elig-13', 'eligibility', 'You passed your FAA Knowledge Test seven months ago and are now ready for your checkride. Is there any issue with the timing?', 'No issue at seven months — the Knowledge Test Report is valid for 24 calendar months from the date you passed it, so you''re well within the window. It''s worth knowing that if it had been closer to or past 24 months, you''d need to retake the knowledge test before the practical test could be conducted.', 'Not knowing the Knowledge Test Report has an expiration at all, or misremembering the actual window as shorter than 24 months.', 'Whether you know the actual validity period rather than guessing, since this determines whether your paperwork is even valid for the exam you''re taking today.', 'Area of Operation I, Task A — Pilot Qualifications (Knowledge).', 'An expired Knowledge Test Report is a real reason a DPE would have to turn an applicant away at the start of a scheduled checkride.', true, null, 12),
  ('elig-14', 'eligibility', 'What is the significance of "category, class, and type" when discussing pilot certificates and ratings, and how does "airplane single-engine land" fit into that structure?', 'Category is a broad classification such as airplane, rotorcraft, or glider. Class is a further division within category, such as single-engine land, multiengine land, or single-engine sea. Type is a specific make/model designation required only for large aircraft, turbojets, or other aircraft the FAA designates as requiring one. "Airplane single-engine land" describes a category and class combination, not a type — a Private Pilot with this rating doesn''t need a further type rating unless flying a large or turbojet-powered airplane.', 'Conflating class with type, or assuming every different airplane model requires its own separate rating.', 'Whether you understand this three-tier structure well enough to know when a new privilege actually requires additional certification and when it doesn''t.', 'Area of Operation I, Task A — Pilot Qualifications (Knowledge).', 'Understanding this structure is what tells you whether stepping up to a different airplane requires a new rating or just a checkout or insurance requirement.', false, null, 13),
  ('elig-15', 'eligibility', 'You''re taking your checkride in an aircraft that isn''t the same one you did most of your training in. Is there anything you need to verify before the exam?', 'Confirm you have any required logbook endorsement showing proficiency in that specific make and model if it''s meaningfully different, and more practically, make sure you''re genuinely comfortable and current in that aircraft''s systems, performance numbers, and checklist flow, since the DPE will expect fluency in whichever aircraft you show up in.', 'Assuming any airplane in the same category and class is interchangeable for checkride purposes without confirming actual proficiency and any required endorsements for that specific aircraft.', 'Whether you recognize that showing up in an unfamiliar aircraft creates real risk on the exam itself, not just a paperwork question.', 'Area of Operation I, Task A — Pilot Qualifications (Knowledge and Risk Management).', 'A DPE evaluates your performance in the specific aircraft you fly that day — genuine unfamiliarity with it undermines your performance regardless of your skill in a different airplane.', true, null, 14),
  ('elig-16', 'eligibility', 'What is a special issuance medical certificate, and when would a pilot need one?', 'A special issuance is an FAA medical certificate granted with specific conditions or monitoring requirements for an applicant who has a medical history or condition that would otherwise disqualify them under standard medical standards, but where the FAA determines the condition can be safely managed. It typically requires periodic additional documentation to maintain.', 'Assuming any significant medical history automatically disqualifies a pilot permanently, without knowing the special issuance pathway exists.', 'Whether you understand this option exists and roughly how it works, even if you personally haven''t needed one.', 'Area of Operation I, Task A — Pilot Qualifications (Knowledge).', 'Many working pilots fly under a special issuance for a managed condition — knowing this pathway exists matters for your own future medical history too.', false, null, 15),
  ('elig-17', 'eligibility', 'You develop a new medical condition after your medical certificate was issued, but before your next required exam. What are your obligations?', 'You must not exercise the privileges of your certificate if you know or have reason to know of a condition that would make you unable to meet the requirements for your medical certificate — this is an ongoing, self-certifying obligation, not something you can defer to your next scheduled medical exam.', 'Assuming the medical certificate remains valid on paper regardless of your actual current condition until its stated expiration date.', 'Whether you understand medical certification as an ongoing personal responsibility, not a one-time exam that clears you until its printed expiration.', 'Area of Operation I, Task A — Pilot Qualifications (Knowledge and Risk Management).', 'This obligation is exactly why honest self-assessment, like IMSAFE, matters between medical exams, not just at them.', true, null, 16),
  ('elig-18', 'eligibility', 'What endorsement, if any, is required for a private pilot to fly a tailwheel aircraft, and why does this requirement exist?', 'A specific logbook endorsement for tailwheel aircraft operation is required, since tailwheel aircraft have meaningfully different ground handling characteristics — susceptibility to ground loop, a different sight picture, and different ground-steering technique — that a pilot trained only in tricycle-gear aircraft hasn''t been exposed to.', 'Assuming a private pilot certificate with airplane single-engine land automatically covers tailwheel aircraft, since it''s technically the same category and class.', 'Whether you know that some privileges require a specific endorsement even within the same broad category and class rating.', 'Area of Operation I, Task A — Pilot Qualifications (Knowledge).', 'Flying a tailwheel aircraft without the specific training and endorsement is both illegal and a real, elevated accident risk given the different handling characteristics.', false, null, 17),
  ('elig-19', 'eligibility', 'Your CFI endorsed your logbook for solo cross-country flight three months ago, but you haven''t flown solo since. Can you use that same endorsement for a solo flight today?', 'A solo endorsement for a student pilot is valid for 90 days. At three months you''re right at or past that edge, so verify the exact date against the endorsement, and if it''s expired, you''ll need a current endorsement from your instructor before flying solo again.', 'Assuming a solo endorsement remains valid indefinitely once given, rather than checking its actual 90-day window.', 'Whether you know solo endorsements carry a real expiration, which matters directly to whether you''re legal to fly solo on a given day.', 'Area of Operation I, Task A — Pilot Qualifications (Knowledge).', 'This is a real, common way a student pilot can unknowingly become illegal to solo — checking the actual endorsement date, not just remembering "I got endorsed a while back," is what keeps you legal.', true, null, 18),
  ('elig-20', 'eligibility', 'What is the purpose of the recent flight experience requirement under 14 CFR 61.57 for carrying passengers, separate from the flight review?', 'To carry passengers, you must have made at least three takeoffs and three landings in an aircraft of the same category and class within the preceding 90 days; for night passenger-carrying, those takeoffs and landings must have been to a full stop, at night, within the preceding 90 days. This is a separate, shorter-window currency requirement from the 24-calendar-month flight review.', 'Confusing this 90-day passenger-carrying currency with the 24-month flight review, treating them as the same requirement.', 'Whether you can keep multiple, differently-timed currency requirements straight rather than collapsing them into one.', 'Area of Operation I, Task A — Pilot Qualifications (Knowledge).', 'A pilot can be current under their flight review but still illegal to carry passengers, or illegal at night specifically, if they haven''t met the shorter 90-day requirement.', false, null, 19),

  -- ═══════════════════ AIRWORTHINESS REQUIREMENTS (+12) ═══════════════════
  ('aw-9', 'airworthiness', 'You preflight the aircraft and notice the ELT''s battery replacement due date on its placard has passed. Is the aircraft airworthy to fly?', 'No — an ELT battery must be replaced, or recharged if rechargeable, at specific intervals defined by regulation, generally after one-half of its useful life has expired or after a specified cumulative use in transmission time. An expired battery due-date means the aircraft doesn''t meet required equipment standards and isn''t airworthy for flight until it''s addressed.', 'Treating an expired ELT battery date as a minor paperwork issue rather than an actual airworthiness and required-equipment problem.', 'Whether you catch a specific, less commonly discussed required-equipment item during a mental preflight review, not just the obvious ones like ARROW documents.', 'Area of Operation I, Task B — Airworthiness Requirements (Knowledge and Risk Management).', 'An ELT is only useful in an actual emergency if its battery is genuinely within its service life — this is a real safety equipment issue, not just a compliance technicality.', true, null, 8),
  ('aw-10', 'airworthiness', 'What is the difference between an Airworthiness Certificate and a Certificate of Registration, and does either of them expire?', 'The Airworthiness Certificate certifies the aircraft meets its approved type design and is in condition for safe operation; a Standard Airworthiness Certificate doesn''t expire as long as the aircraft continues to meet its airworthiness requirements. The Certificate of Registration establishes legal ownership and registration and must be renewed periodically per current FAA registration rules.', 'Assuming both documents expire on the same schedule, or that the Airworthiness Certificate itself needs periodic renewal the way registration does.', 'Whether you understand these two required documents serve entirely different purposes with different validity rules.', 'Area of Operation I, Task B — Airworthiness Requirements (Knowledge).', 'Confusing these two documents could mean missing an actual registration renewal deadline while assuming the airworthiness certificate covers everything.', false, null, 9),
  ('aw-11', 'airworthiness', 'You find a logbook entry showing the aircraft''s transponder was last certified two and a half years ago. Is the aircraft legal to fly in controlled airspace requiring a transponder?', 'No — the transponder and its associated altitude reporting equipment must be tested and inspected within the preceding 24 calendar months. At two and a half years that inspection has lapsed, and the aircraft isn''t legal to operate in airspace requiring a functioning, current transponder until it''s retested.', 'Confusing the transponder''s 24-month check with the pitot-static system''s separate 24-month check — both exist, and both matter, but they''re distinct inspections.', 'Whether you know the specific interval and can recognize when it''s lapsed from a logbook entry, not just that "some check" is required.', 'Area of Operation I, Task B — Airworthiness Requirements (Knowledge).', 'An expired transponder check is a real, checkable item that can ground an otherwise airworthy aircraft for controlled-airspace operations.', true, null, 10),
  ('aw-12', 'airworthiness', 'What is the difference between an inspection interval measured in "time in service," such as a 100-hour inspection, versus one measured in calendar time, such as an annual inspection — and why does that distinction matter for an aircraft that flies infrequently?', 'Time-in-service intervals are based on actual flight hours accumulated, while calendar-time intervals are based on elapsed time regardless of how much the aircraft has actually flown. An infrequently flown aircraft can go a long time without triggering a 100-hour inspection by flight hours alone, but it still comes due for its annual and other calendar-based inspections purely because time has passed, even with very little flying in between.', 'Assuming an aircraft that hasn''t flown much is exempt from calendar-based inspections just because it hasn''t accumulated many flight hours.', 'Whether you understand these two types of intervals run independently, and an aircraft can be non-compliant on one even while clearly compliant on the other.', 'Area of Operation I, Task B — Airworthiness Requirements (Knowledge).', 'An infrequently flown aircraft is a real, common way for a calendar-based inspection to lapse quietly while the owner assumes low usage means everything''s still current.', false, null, 11),
  ('aw-13', 'airworthiness', 'You''re preflighting a rental aircraft and can''t immediately find the aircraft maintenance logbooks in the plane. How do you determine whether the aircraft is currently airworthy?', 'Maintenance logbooks aren''t required to be carried in the aircraft — check with the FBO or owner for the logbooks or maintenance records showing current annual and 100-hour status, AD compliance, and other required inspections. Don''t assume airworthiness just because the aircraft "looks fine" or was flown recently by someone else.', 'Assuming a rental aircraft is automatically airworthy because it''s available to rent, without verifying actual maintenance status through the records.', 'Whether you know maintenance records don''t have to be in the aircraft, and where to actually go to verify status rather than skipping the check.', 'Area of Operation I, Task B — Airworthiness Requirements (Knowledge and Risk Management).', 'As PIC you''re responsible for verifying airworthiness regardless of whether you personally own the aircraft — "someone else probably checked" isn''t a legal or safe standard.', true, null, 12),
  ('aw-14', 'airworthiness', 'What is the difference between a manufacturer''s Service Bulletin and an FAA Airworthiness Directive, and which one is mandatory?', 'A Service Bulletin is issued by the manufacturer and is generally a recommendation, not legally mandatory unless referenced by an AD. An Airworthiness Directive is issued by the FAA and is legally mandatory, addressing an unsafe condition that must be corrected within the AD''s specified compliance time or method.', 'Treating a Service Bulletin as legally required in the same way an AD is, or assuming ADs are merely recommendations.', 'Whether you understand which document actually carries legal force, since applicants sometimes conflate manufacturer guidance with FAA mandate.', 'Area of Operation I, Task B — Airworthiness Requirements (Knowledge).', 'Confusing a recommended Service Bulletin with a mandatory AD could lead an owner or pilot to believe compliance is optional when it''s actually required by law.', false, null, 13),
  ('aw-15', 'airworthiness', 'The mechanic who signed off your last annual inspection wrote that the aircraft was found airworthy, but you notice a placard is missing from the panel that you remember being there before. What do you do?', 'A signed-off annual doesn''t override your own preflight responsibility — investigate the missing placard, since some placards are themselves required equipment. If it''s a required placard, the aircraft may not currently be airworthy regardless of the annual sign-off, and the discrepancy should be resolved with maintenance before flight.', 'Assuming a signed annual inspection guarantees the aircraft is airworthy in its exact current state, rather than treating your own preflight as an independent, ongoing verification.', 'Whether you treat PIC preflight responsibility as independent from, not superseded by, a mechanic''s prior sign-off.', 'Area of Operation I, Task B — Airworthiness Requirements (Risk Management).', 'Aircraft condition can change between an annual inspection and today''s flight — your own preflight is the last line of defense, not a formality after a mechanic has already looked at it.', true, null, 14),
  ('aw-16', 'airworthiness', 'What does it mean for an aircraft alteration to be a "major alteration," and how does that affect the aircraft''s airworthiness documentation?', 'A major alteration is one that could appreciably affect weight, balance, structural strength, performance, powerplant operation, flight characteristics, or other qualities affecting airworthiness, and isn''t done according to accepted practices or elementary operations. A major alteration requires proper documentation, typically FAA Form 337, and must be performed or approved by appropriately authorized personnel, becoming part of the aircraft''s permanent records.', 'Assuming any modification to the aircraft is automatically a "minor" change that doesn''t need special documentation.', 'Whether you understand that some changes carry a formal documentation and approval requirement beyond a simple logbook entry.', 'Area of Operation I, Task B — Airworthiness Requirements (Knowledge).', 'An undocumented major alteration can affect an aircraft''s legal airworthiness status even if the modification itself was done competently.', false, null, 15),
  ('aw-17', 'airworthiness', 'You''re about to depart and notice a placard is present, but the wording doesn''t match what you remember from your training aircraft''s checklist regarding a specific operating limitation. What should you do?', 'Treat placards as authoritative, aircraft-specific limitations that can genuinely differ between individual aircraft, even the same make and model, due to equipment differences or specific alterations. Follow the actual placard in the aircraft you''re flying rather than what you remember from a different aircraft, and clarify with an instructor or mechanic if something seems inconsistent with the POH.', 'Assuming every aircraft of the same make and model has identical placards and limitations, when equipment and modifications can create real differences.', 'Whether you treat the specific aircraft in front of you as the authority, not your memory of a similar one.', 'Area of Operation I, Task B — Airworthiness Requirements (Knowledge).', 'Two aircraft of the same model can have genuinely different operating limitations due to installed equipment — flying by memory instead of the actual placard is a real, avoidable risk.', true, null, 16),
  ('aw-18', 'airworthiness', 'What is required for an aircraft''s static system and altimeter system to remain legal for flight into airspace requiring IFR operations or Class A airspace transit?', 'The static pressure system, altimeter, and automatic altitude reporting equipment must be tested and inspected within the preceding 24 calendar months under 14 CFR 91.411, in addition to the general transponder check under 91.413 — both are required for IFR flight, and both share the same 24-month interval though they''re separate checks.', 'Treating the pitot-static and altimeter check and the transponder check as a single combined requirement rather than two related but distinct inspections.', 'Whether you can name the specific regulatory requirement rather than a vague "it gets checked periodically" answer.', 'Area of Operation I, Task B — Airworthiness Requirements (Knowledge).', 'A pilot planning an IFR flight, or any flight requiring these systems, needs to verify both checks independently rather than assuming one covers the other.', false, null, 17),
  ('aw-19', 'airworthiness', 'During preflight, you find a small area of wing skin damage smaller than what your POH''s inspection criteria describes as a limit for continued flight. Do you go?', 'If the damage is genuinely within the manufacturer''s published limits for continued flight without repair, the aircraft may still be airworthy — but verify this against the actual documented limit rather than a personal guess, and if there''s any doubt, defer to a mechanic before flight.', 'Making a personal judgment call about acceptable damage without referencing the actual documented limit, or assuming any visible damage automatically grounds the aircraft.', 'Whether you know to check documented limits rather than eyeballing a subjective judgment either way.', 'Area of Operation I, Task B — Airworthiness Requirements (Risk Management).', 'PIC judgment about airworthiness should be grounded in actual documentation, not a guess in either direction — too conservative wastes a flight unnecessarily, too permissive risks flying an unsafe aircraft.', true, null, 18),
  ('aw-20', 'airworthiness', 'What is the difference between the "condition inspection" required for an Experimental Amateur-Built aircraft and the "annual inspection" required for a standard-category aircraft?', 'A condition inspection for an Experimental Amateur-Built aircraft is required every 12 calendar months, the same interval as an annual, and can be performed by the aircraft''s builder if they hold a repairman certificate for that specific aircraft, or by an A&P mechanic. A standard-category aircraft''s annual inspection must be performed by an A&P mechanic holding Inspection Authorization, and can''t be performed by an owner-builder regardless of certificates held.', 'Assuming the same personnel requirements apply to both aircraft categories, or not knowing Experimental aircraft have a distinctly named inspection with different authorized-personnel rules.', 'Whether you know these are structurally different systems, not just different names for the same requirement.', 'Area of Operation I, Task B — Airworthiness Requirements (Knowledge).', 'A pilot who flies or is considering an Experimental aircraft needs to know this distinction is real, not just terminology, since it changes who can legally perform the inspection.', false, null, 19),

  -- ═══════════════════ PERFORMANCE AND LIMITATIONS (+12) ═══════════════════
  ('perf-9', 'performance', 'Your calculated takeoff distance over a 50-foot obstacle comes out to 1,400 feet, and the runway available is 1,600 feet with a tree line right at the departure end. The numbers technically work. Would you actually make this takeoff, and what would change your answer?', 'A 200-foot margin, about 14%, against book numbers that assume a new aircraft, ideal pilot technique, and no wind is thin, especially with an obstacle right at the departure end rather than open terrain beyond the runway. A strong applicant wants a larger real margin — many use roughly 1.5x book distance as a personal minimum — and would want to confirm actual wind, temperature, and aircraft condition before committing, delaying, reducing weight, or choosing a different runway if the margin doesn''t hold up.', 'Treating the exact book number as a hard go/no-go line rather than building in a personal margin for real-world variables the book doesn''t capture, especially with a real obstacle at the runway end rather than open space.', 'Whether you apply real judgment on top of a chart number rather than treating "the chart says yes" as the end of the analysis.', 'Area of Operation I, Task F — Performance and Limitations (Risk Management).', 'Book performance numbers assume a new aircraft and ideal technique — real-world margins, especially with a fixed obstacle right at the runway end, protect you from the gap between charted and actual performance.', true, null, 8),
  ('perf-10', 'performance', 'What is the difference between "useful load" and "payload," and why does that distinction matter when planning a flight with passengers and baggage?', 'Useful load is the difference between an aircraft''s maximum gross weight and its empty weight — it includes fuel, oil if not part of empty weight, crew, passengers, and baggage. Payload is useful load minus the weight of fuel, and sometimes oil — essentially what''s left for people and baggage once fuel is accounted for. Confusing the two can lead a pilot to think they have more capacity for people and bags than they actually do once a full fuel load is factored in.', 'Using useful load and payload interchangeably when planning weight and balance with a full fuel load.', 'Whether you understand these represent genuinely different available weights, not synonyms.', 'Area of Operation I, Task F — Performance and Limitations (Knowledge).', 'A pilot who confuses payload with useful load can genuinely miscalculate how many passengers and how much baggage the aircraft can safely carry with full fuel.', false, null, 9),
  ('perf-11', 'performance', 'You''re loading the aircraft and realize that with full fuel, you''re within max gross weight, but your calculated CG falls just outside the aft limit. What are your options?', 'Reduce weight in the aft-loaded areas, redistribute weight forward if possible, or reduce fuel load and plan a fuel stop en route if range allows. You cannot legally or safely fly with the CG outside limits regardless of remaining under max gross weight, since weight and CG are independent limits that both must be satisfied.', 'Assuming being within max gross weight is sufficient by itself, without separately confirming CG falls within its own limits.', 'Whether you understand weight and balance as two independent checks, not one combined pass/fail number.', 'Area of Operation I, Task F — Performance and Limitations (Knowledge and Risk Management).', 'An aircraft can be well under max gross weight and still be dangerously out of CG limits — both checks matter independently, every time.', true, null, 10),
  ('perf-12', 'performance', 'How does high density altitude specifically affect propeller efficiency, separate from its effect on engine power output?', 'In addition to reducing engine power output, since the engine takes in less air mass per intake stroke, high density altitude reduces propeller efficiency because the propeller is also an airfoil operating in thinner air, generating less thrust for a given RPM and blade angle than it would at sea-level density. Both power available and the propeller''s ability to convert that power into thrust are reduced simultaneously.', 'Only discussing density altitude''s effect on the engine, missing that the propeller itself is separately less effective in thin air.', 'Whether you understand density altitude degrades performance through two separate mechanisms, not just one.', 'Area of Operation I, Task F — Performance and Limitations (Knowledge).', 'This compounding effect is exactly why high-density-altitude takeoff performance degrades more dramatically than pilots sometimes expect from engine power loss alone.', false, null, 11),
  ('perf-13', 'performance', 'You''re planning a flight out of a high-elevation airport on a warm afternoon, and your computed density altitude is over 7,000 feet, though the field elevation is only 5,000 feet. Walk me through how you''d adjust your plan.', 'Use the density altitude, not the field elevation, to compute actual takeoff and climb performance from the appropriate charts. Expect meaningfully longer takeoff roll and reduced climb rate than the field elevation alone would suggest, consider a lighter load, plan for the coolest part of the day if possible, and confirm real obstacle clearance margins given the degraded climb performance.', 'Using field elevation instead of computed density altitude when referencing performance charts, understating the actual performance penalty.', 'Whether you correctly use density altitude, not field elevation, as the actual input to performance planning.', 'Area of Operation I, Task F — Performance and Limitations (Risk Management).', 'High-density-altitude airports are a well-documented setting for takeoff performance accidents specifically because pilots under-adjust for the gap between field elevation and actual density altitude.', true, null, 12),
  ('perf-14', 'performance', 'What is the difference between accelerate-stop distance and accelerate-go distance, and for which category of aircraft is this typically a formal, published consideration?', 'Accelerate-stop distance is the distance needed to accelerate to a specific speed and then stop if the takeoff is aborted; accelerate-go distance is the distance needed to accelerate to that speed, continue takeoff, and clear obstacles even with an engine failure at that critical point. These are formal, published performance figures required for multi-engine and larger, transport-category aircraft; single-engine trainers generally don''t have this exact published data, though the underlying judgment — knowing your abort point — still applies informally.', 'Assuming this concept doesn''t apply at all to single-engine training, missing that the underlying judgment concept is still valuable even without formal published numbers.', 'Whether you understand both the formal concept and its informal relevance to your own training aircraft.', 'Area of Operation I, Task F — Performance and Limitations (Knowledge).', 'Even without published accelerate-stop and accelerate-go numbers, deciding your personal abort point on a specific runway before every takeoff is exactly this concept applied informally.', false, null, 13),
  ('perf-15', 'performance', 'You''re flying with three passengers and full fuel, close to max gross weight, and departing from a shorter-than-usual runway. What specific performance numbers do you want to double-check before committing to the takeoff, and why?', 'Double-check takeoff distance, ground roll and total distance over a 50-foot obstacle, at your actual weight, density altitude, and wind condition, plus your climb gradient and rate for any departure obstacles, since heavier weight simultaneously increases required takeoff distance and reduces climb performance — the two effects compound exactly when you can least afford it on a short runway.', 'Checking only ground roll distance without also confirming climb performance is adequate to clear departure obstacles at the heavier weight.', 'Whether you recognize that weight affects both takeoff distance and climb performance together, not just one or the other.', 'Area of Operation I, Task F — Performance and Limitations (Risk Management).', 'A heavier airplane needs more runway and climbs worse over obstacles at the same time — checking both together, not separately, is what a real pre-takeoff risk assessment requires.', true, null, 14),
  ('perf-16', 'performance', 'What does "never exceed speed" (VNE) represent, and why is it typically shown as a red radial line rather than the top of a colored arc on the airspeed indicator?', 'VNE is the maximum speed at which the aircraft can be operated without risking structural damage or failure, under any circumstances, including a dive. It''s shown as a single red radial line, distinct from arcs which represent ranges, because it''s an absolute limit with no safe margin above it, unlike the yellow caution range, which is conditionally acceptable in smooth air.', 'Treating VNE like the top of the yellow arc, as if there were a safe operating margin above it under the right conditions.', 'Whether you understand VNE as an absolute, no-exception structural limit rather than a caution threshold.', 'Area of Operation I, Task F — Performance and Limitations (Knowledge).', 'Confusing VNE with a soft caution limit like the yellow arc could lead a pilot to believe brief excursions above it are acceptable, when they genuinely risk structural failure.', false, null, 15),
  ('perf-17', 'performance', 'You''re planning a flight at cruise altitude and need to calculate your true airspeed from your indicated airspeed for fuel and navigation planning. Walk me through the general relationship and why it matters.', 'True airspeed is generally higher than indicated or calibrated airspeed at altitude, since air density decreases with altitude and the airspeed indicator under-reads relative to true airspeed as density drops. Using true airspeed, adjusted for temperature and altitude, rather than indicated airspeed for your groundspeed and time/fuel calculations is what makes your cross-country planning numbers accurate.', 'Using indicated airspeed directly in navigation log calculations without correcting to true airspeed for higher cruising altitudes.', 'Whether you know why this correction matters practically, not just that a difference exists.', 'Area of Operation I, Task F — Performance and Limitations (Knowledge).', 'Using indicated instead of true airspeed in your flight planning can produce a meaningfully wrong time-en-route and fuel burn estimate, especially at higher cruising altitudes.', true, null, 16),
  ('perf-18', 'performance', 'What is load factor, and how does it change in a coordinated, level turn as bank angle increases?', 'Load factor is the ratio of the total aerodynamic force supported by the wings to the aircraft''s actual weight, expressed in Gs. In a coordinated, level turn, load factor increases with bank angle — roughly 1.41G at a 45-degree bank and about 2G at a 60-degree bank — and this increase is why stall speed also rises in a steep turn, since the wing must generate more lift at the same airspeed to maintain altitude.', 'Not connecting increased load factor in a turn to the corresponding increase in stall speed, treating the two as unrelated facts.', 'Whether you connect load factor to its direct real-world consequence — an elevated stall speed in the turn — not just the numeric definition.', 'Area of Operation I, Task F — Performance and Limitations (Knowledge).', 'This relationship is the direct aerodynamic mechanism behind accelerated stalls in steep turns, including the base-to-final turn stall/spin accident pattern.', false, null, 17),
  ('perf-19', 'performance', 'You''re calculating landing distance for a wet, grass runway at your destination, but your POH''s landing distance chart only publishes numbers for a dry, paved runway. How do you adjust?', 'Apply the specific adjustment factors your POH provides for surface conditions if published, since many POHs give a percentage increase for grass or wet or contaminated surfaces. If no specific factor is published, apply a conservative estimate based on general guidance and build in additional margin given the uncertainty, since landing performance on a non-ideal surface can be significantly worse than the dry, paved baseline.', 'Using the dry, paved runway number directly without any adjustment for a meaningfully different surface condition.', 'Whether you know to actively adjust the baseline chart number for real surface conditions rather than treating the published figure as universally applicable.', 'Area of Operation I, Task F — Performance and Limitations (Risk Management).', 'Landing long or with reduced braking effectiveness on a wet or soft surface, using an unadjusted dry-runway number, is a real and preventable landing-overrun risk.', true, null, 18),
  ('perf-20', 'performance', 'What is the relationship between an aircraft''s weight and its stall speed, and how does that connect to your approach speed planning?', 'Stall speed increases as weight increases, since a heavier aircraft needs more lift, and therefore a higher angle of attack or airspeed, to remain airborne at a given configuration. Since normal approach speed is typically set as a multiple of stall speed, often around 1.3 Vso, a heavier aircraft should fly a proportionally higher approach speed than the same aircraft at a lighter weight, or you risk approaching too slowly relative to its actual stall speed that day.', 'Using the same fixed approach speed regardless of actual aircraft weight, rather than adjusting for the fact that stall speed itself shifts with weight.', 'Whether you connect weight, stall speed, and approach speed as a chain of cause and effect rather than treating approach speed as a fixed number.', 'Area of Operation I, Task F — Performance and Limitations (Knowledge).', 'Flying a fixed approach speed regardless of actual weight can mean flying with less real margin above stall than you assume on a heavier day.', false, null, 19),

  -- ═══════════════════ CROSS-COUNTRY PLANNING (+14) ═══════════════════
  ('xc-9', 'crosscountry', 'You''re planning a 250 nm VFR cross-country and trying to decide between a direct route and one that follows a highway with more emergency landing options. How do you actually weigh this decision?', 'Weigh the time and fuel savings of the direct route against the safety margin of better emergency landing options and easier visual navigation along a route with more identifiable checkpoints. Over terrain with few suitable off-airport landing sites, the modest time cost of a slightly longer route following more hospitable terrain or a highway is often a reasonable trade for meaningfully better options in an engine-out scenario.', 'Defaulting to the shortest or fastest route without weighing the terrain and emergency-landing-option trade-off it represents.', 'Whether you treat route selection itself as a risk-management decision, not just a time and fuel optimization.', 'Area of Operation I, Task D — Cross-Country Flight Planning (Risk Management).', 'Route selection is one of the easiest, lowest-cost risk-management decisions available before you ever start the engine.', true, null, 8),
  ('xc-10', 'crosscountry', 'What is the difference between true course, magnetic course, and compass heading, and what causes the differences between them?', 'True course is your intended path measured from true north on the chart. Magnetic course applies variation — the difference between true and magnetic north at your location — to convert to a magnetic reference. Compass heading further applies deviation, compass-specific error from local magnetic influences in the aircraft, and any wind correction angle needed to actually fly the intended course over the ground.', 'Skipping variation or deviation corrections, or applying them in the wrong direction.', 'Whether you can walk through the full true-to-compass conversion chain accurately, not just recite that variation and deviation exist.', 'Area of Operation I, Task D — Cross-Country Flight Planning (Knowledge).', 'An error in this conversion chain, even a small one, compounds over a long cross-country into a real navigation error.', false, null, 9),
  ('xc-11', 'crosscountry', 'Thirty minutes into your cross-country, your groundspeed is noticeably slower than you planned, and your fuel burn is tracking higher than expected. What do you do?', 'Recompute your revised time en route and fuel required to your destination and any alternate based on actual observed groundspeed and fuel burn, not your original flight-planned numbers. If the revised numbers show you''d arrive with less than your required reserve, adjust now — divert to a closer fuel stop or reconsider the flight — rather than continuing and hoping conditions improve.', 'Continuing on the original flight plan numbers despite observed performance showing a worse outcome, rather than recalculating in real time.', 'Whether you actually use in-flight observed data to update your plan, rather than treating the preflight plan as fixed regardless of what''s actually happening.', 'Area of Operation I, Task D — Cross-Country Flight Planning (Risk Management).', 'Fuel exhaustion accidents are frequently traced back to a pilot noticing worse-than-planned performance and continuing anyway rather than recalculating and adjusting.', true, null, 10),
  ('xc-12', 'crosscountry', 'What information does a sectional chart''s shaded relief and contour lines convey, and how do you use that for a cross-country over unfamiliar, mountainous terrain?', 'Contour lines and shaded relief show terrain elevation and its rate of change — closely spaced contour lines indicate steep terrain, and maximum elevation figures in each chart quadrangle give the highest elevation, including obstacles, to plan a safe altitude with real terrain clearance margin, not just legal cloud clearance.', 'Planning cruising altitude based only on legal VFR cruising altitude rules without cross-checking actual terrain elevation and obstacles along the route.', 'Whether you use terrain information proactively in altitude planning, not just as a chart-reading exercise.', 'Area of Operation I, Task D — Cross-Country Flight Planning (Knowledge and Risk Management).', 'Choosing a cruising altitude that''s legal but doesn''t provide real terrain clearance margin over mountainous terrain is a documented cause of controlled flight into terrain.', true, null, 11),
  ('xc-13', 'crosscountry', 'What is the maximum elevation figure (MEF) shown in each quadrangle of a sectional chart, and what margin is already built into it?', 'The MEF represents the highest terrain or obstacle elevation within that chart quadrangle, rounded up to the next 100-foot increment, with a built-in obstruction clearance value — generally 100 feet for verified obstacles and up to 300 feet for less certain data — meaning the MEF already includes a safety buffer above the actual highest point.', 'Treating the MEF as the exact highest point with no margin, or not knowing it already includes a buffer above actual terrain or obstacle height.', 'Whether you know both what the figure represents and that a margin is already built in, which affects how much additional buffer you personally need to add.', 'Area of Operation I, Task D — Cross-Country Flight Planning (Knowledge).', 'Knowing the MEF already includes a margin helps you make a more precise altitude decision rather than over- or under-padding your own additional buffer.', false, null, 12),
  ('xc-14', 'crosscountry', 'You''re 40 miles into a cross-country and notice a NOTAM you missed during planning: a large TFR has gone into effect over the second half of your route. What do you do?', 'Land as soon as practical to properly research the TFR''s exact boundaries, altitude, and duration rather than attempting to route around it based on incomplete in-flight information. Contact Flight Service or ATC for guidance if continuing seems necessary, but the safest response to discovering a missed TFR in flight is to get it fully resolved on the ground before proceeding.', 'Attempting to route around a TFR based on incomplete information gathered in flight, rather than getting a full, accurate picture before proceeding.', 'Whether you treat a missed NOTAM as a serious gap requiring a real stop to resolve, not something to guess your way around in flight.', 'Area of Operation I, Task D — Cross-Country Flight Planning (Risk Management).', 'TFR violations carry serious enforcement consequences, and attempting to navigate around one with incomplete in-flight information is genuinely riskier than landing to get it right.', true, null, 13),
  ('xc-15', 'crosscountry', 'What is the "1-in-60 rule," and how can you use it to correct a cross-country track error without a GPS?', 'The 1-in-60 rule approximates that 1 degree of heading error results in roughly 1 nautical mile of track deviation for every 60 nautical miles flown. If you find yourself off course by a known distance after a known distance flown, you can calculate the heading correction needed both to correct back to your original course and to a new course directly to your destination.', 'Not knowing this rule of thumb exists as a manual, chart-independent correction method, relying entirely on GPS for course correction.', 'Whether you have a manual navigation skill as a backup, not total dependence on electronic navigation.', 'Area of Operation I, Task D — Cross-Country Flight Planning (Knowledge).', 'A GPS failure on a cross-country doesn''t have to become an emergency if you have a real, practiced manual correction method available.', false, null, 14),
  ('xc-16', 'crosscountry', 'You''re navigating primarily by pilotage on a cross-country, and the visible landmarks you planned to use turn out to be harder to identify than expected due to haze. What''s your backup plan?', 'Fall back to dead reckoning using your planned headings, groundspeed, and elapsed time to estimate position, cross-check with any available VOR or GPS as a secondary confirmation even if not your primary method, and if position becomes genuinely uncertain, use the lost procedures — climb, communicate, confess, comply — rather than continuing to guess.', 'Continuing to search for landmarks with increasing uncertainty rather than falling back to a systematic backup method or admitting uncertainty early.', 'Whether you have an actual layered backup plan for degraded visual navigation conditions, not just one primary method with no fallback.', 'Area of Operation I, Task D — Cross-Country Flight Planning (Risk Management).', 'Haze and reduced visibility genuinely degrade pilotage — having dead reckoning and electronic backups ready before you need them prevents a minor visibility issue from becoming a lost-procedure emergency.', true, null, 15),
  ('xc-17', 'crosscountry', 'What does it mean to "open" and "close" a VFR flight plan, and what actually happens if you forget to close one?', 'Opening activates the flight plan with Flight Service once airborne so search-and-rescue timing begins tracking against your filed information; closing tells Flight Service you''ve landed safely so tracking stops. If you forget to close it, Flight Service will attempt to contact you, and if unsuccessful, will eventually initiate search-and-rescue procedures based on your filed route and times — a real cost and real resources triggered by an administrative oversight.', 'Treating flight plan closure as optional or unimportant, not realizing it directly triggers a real search-and-rescue response if skipped.', 'Whether you understand the real consequence of forgetting to close a flight plan, not just the mechanical steps of filing one.', 'Area of Operation I, Task D — Cross-Country Flight Planning (Knowledge and Risk Management).', 'Search-and-rescue resources are a real, finite resource — forgetting to close a flight plan wastes them on a false alarm and delays response to an actual emergency elsewhere.', false, null, 16),
  ('xc-18', 'crosscountry', 'You''re planning a cross-country that will have you landing right around sunset. What additional planning considerations does that trigger?', 'Confirm your ETA leaves adequate margin before official sunset or end of civil twilight if you''re not comfortable with or current for night operations, verify your aircraft has the required equipment for night flight if you might land after sunset, and build in extra time buffer since a delay could push you into genuinely different lighting and currency requirements.', 'Planning tightly to exactly civil twilight or sunset without a real buffer for delays that could push the actual landing into night conditions you''re not prepared or equipped for.', 'Whether you proactively plan for a lighting-condition transition rather than treating sunset as an afterthought.', 'Area of Operation I, Task D — Cross-Country Flight Planning (Risk Management).', 'A delay of even 20-30 minutes near sunset can change a flight from day VFR to a night operation with different equipment, currency, and personal-comfort requirements.', true, null, 17),
  ('xc-19', 'crosscountry', 'What is the difference between the estimated time en route (ETE) on your flight plan and your required fuel reserve calculation — why can''t you simply fuel for exactly your planned ETE?', 'ETE is your best estimate of flight time based on planned groundspeed; required fuel reserve, 45 minutes at normal cruise for day VFR, more for night or IFR, exists specifically to cover the difference between estimated and actual conditions — stronger-than-forecast headwinds, a hold, a missed approach, or a diversion. Fueling for exactly your ETE with no reserve assumes your estimate will be perfectly accurate, which real flights routinely aren''t.', 'Treating the minimum legal reserve as a buffer built into the ETE itself rather than as fuel that must be present in addition to a realistic ETE estimate.', 'Whether you understand the reserve requirement exists precisely because estimates are imperfect, not as a redundant safety margin on top of an already-conservative estimate.', 'Area of Operation I, Task D — Cross-Country Flight Planning (Knowledge and Risk Management).', 'Fuel exhaustion accidents are frequently traced to a pilot treating the legal reserve as optional padding rather than a mandatory buffer against real-world estimate error.', false, null, 18),
  ('xc-20', 'crosscountry', 'You planned your cross-country using a specific VOR for a portion of your route, but on the day of the flight you notice a NOTAM saying that VOR is out of service for maintenance. How does this change your plan?', 'Substitute an alternate means of navigation for that segment — a different VOR if one provides usable coverage, GPS if equipped and current, or pilotage and dead reckoning — and update your navigation log accordingly before departure rather than discovering the gap in flight. This is exactly why checking NOTAMs for navigational aid status is part of a complete preflight briefing, not just airport and airspace NOTAMs.', 'Only checking NOTAMs for your departure and destination airports, missing NOTAMs affecting navigational aids along the route itself.', 'Whether your NOTAM review is thorough enough to catch a navaid outage before it becomes an in-flight surprise.', 'Area of Operation I, Task D — Cross-Country Flight Planning (Risk Management).', 'Discovering a planned VOR is out of service after you''re already airborne is a preventable, avoidable in-flight complication if the NOTAM check was thorough on the ground.', true, null, 19),
  ('xc-21', 'crosscountry', 'What is the difference between a VFR waypoint and a standard VOR or GPS fix in terms of how they''re depicted and used for cross-country navigation?', 'A VFR waypoint is typically a charted, named point used specifically for VFR GPS navigation and flight plan filing, often near a visual landmark, without being tied to a ground-based navaid. A VOR fix or standard GPS fix may be defined by radials and distances from ground stations or by defined coordinates used more broadly across both VFR and IFR navigation. VFR waypoints exist specifically to give VFR GPS users a convenient, named reference point.', 'Assuming a VFR waypoint has the same regulatory or navigational status as a charted VOR fix, when they serve a specifically VFR-GPS-oriented purpose.', 'Whether you know this specific chart symbol and its intended purpose, since it''s a commonly overlooked chart-reading detail.', 'Area of Operation I, Task D — Cross-Country Flight Planning (Knowledge).', 'Correctly using VFR waypoints makes GPS-based flight planning and filing more precise and simpler to communicate to ATC or Flight Service.', false, null, 20),
  ('xc-22', 'crosscountry', 'You''re planning fuel stops for a longer cross-country and trying to decide between one longer leg with a single fuel stop, or two shorter legs with two stops. How do you actually make this decision?', 'Weigh total trip time against the practical value of more frequent weather-reassessment and fuel-margin checkpoints. On a route with meaningful weather uncertainty, or where reserve margins would be thin on the single long leg, more frequent stops with reassessment opportunities is often the lower-risk choice even if it adds total trip time.', 'Optimizing purely for the fewest stops and shortest total time without weighing the safety value of more frequent weather-reassessment and fuel-margin checkpoints.', 'Whether you treat fuel-stop planning as a real risk-management decision, not purely a time-efficiency question.', 'Area of Operation I, Task D — Cross-Country Flight Planning (Risk Management).', 'More frequent stops on an uncertain-weather day cost time but buy you more decision points to reassess before conditions can trap you far from an alternate.', true, null, 21);
